/td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> gif vs. jpeg for black and white art?</span><hr size=1>  I have heard that it is better to save black and white line art as a gif rather than a jpeg since it results in a smaller file size and won't introduce artifacts into the picture. When I tried saving some line art in Photoshop as a gif file, the file size was bigger than the jpeg file. Did I misunderstand or do I have to change around any options in Photoshop to do this correctly? Lastly, is it indeed better for black and white line art to be saved as a gif rather than a jpeg? Thanks. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon2.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/upolykarbon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Polykarbon</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/pkmini.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sensei</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/29/01 8:53:51 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/googiepat.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: gif vs. jpeg for black and white art?</span><hr size=1> Jpegs are only good for continuous tone images like a photograph or something with a lot of varied gradients and tones.<br>
<br>
Gifs are better for flat fills. <p><b><i>I am Pat's Signature</i></b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ugenn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>genn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/29/01 8:55:49 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://myst.org/ithil/doh.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: gif vs. jpeg for black and white art?</span><hr size=1> If it's line art it's probably a good thing to save as gif, that is if you really want to save up space. Usually a b&amp;w jpg won't take too much space if you save it around the quality setting of 6-7.<br>
<br>
The reason why the file was still big is because you have to lower the ammount of colour in the picture. Go to image&gt;mode&gt;indexed mode and play with the settings there. The lower the colours, the smaller the file size. It's a trial and error process, but it can be very useful (especially if you're trying to make web graphics smaller...) <p><a href="http://myst.org/ithil" target="ithilien"><img src="http://myst.org/ithil/button20.gif" border="0" alt="ithil"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ujefm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>jefm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/29/01 5:46:36 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: gif vs. jpeg for black and white art?</span><hr size=1> As pat said jpgs are best for stuff with gradients..<br>
with psp you can export a file as a gif and compress it untill its rediculously small with very low quality loss...PSP lets you select how many colors ect...I don`t use Photo shop but I imagine its the same <p>--
